Tangent is a 24-month programme providing up to S$200,000 per participant for young people aged 18-25 in Singapore who want to build something on their own terms. The right candidate doesn’t have to be your top academic student, doesn’t have to be hyper-technical (or even a little bit technical), nor do they have to have a very refined idea to work on — it’s more likely to be the one with the seed of idea they keep talking about, or the one who is motivated and self-directed but restless within the conventional system.

Art and design is an underrecognised source of that kind of person. They are already producers comfortable with ambiguity, used to iteration, and practiced at making something. What's often missing is the confidence that a creative practice can be monetised and generate real, sustainable income beyond conventional career paths such as joining a design agency.

Tangent starts with a four-week programme: S$1,000, access to AI tools, and human guides and a wide range of mentoring options. There is no mandatory coursework, no compulsory assignments. Participants self-define the work they want to do on their idea (Tangent staff will help them clarify and refine their ideas) and show us their results at the end of four weeks. There are no further obligations. Those who want to can pitch to continue into the longer programme as well.
Two things that might be worth exploring together:
- Referring individuals whose practice is ready for this kind of development 
- Connecting Tangent with faculty or programme coordinators who work closely with students 

So if you know any youths who belongs in Tangent, please refer them. And if you know other referrers who should know about this, please pass it on.

tangent.org.sg has details on the programme and how it works, how to apply, how to refer someone, and how to get involved as a guide.

